<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> DiTomaso and Healey (2007) considered these trees as invasive in California. These trees are evergreen with aromatic compound leaves. Birds disperse the colored fruits allowing seedlings to establish in wildland vegetation. The trees are common ornamentals that have escaped from cultivation. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Schinus molle, </i>the Peruvian pepper tree, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited<i>. </i>It grows to 15 m tall with slender, drooping branches and compound leaves with narrowly lanceolate leaflets. Small red to pink drupes with a peppery fragrance develop in spring and persist on the plants throughout winter. It is a native of Peru (Wagner et al<i>. </i>1999). <i>S. molle </i>occurs in riparian sites of southern California, and the invasive <i>Phoenix canariensis </i>and <i>Washingtonia robusta </i>may occur with it<i>. <br/>
<br/>
</i>  <i>Schinus terebinthifolius, </i>the Brazilian pepper tree, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited<i>. </i>It grows to 18 m tall with stiff, spreading branches and compound leaves with elliptic leaflets. Small red to pink drupes develop in spring and mature in the fall. It is a native of Brazil (Randall 2000). Currently, no quantitative data exist for stands dominated by this species. <br/>
<br/>
Similarly, <i>Myoporum laetum </i>occurs in central and southern California, as an escaped ornamental to 10 m tall. <i>M. laetum, </i>the ngaio tree, has Cal-IPC rank of Moderate, and it is a native of New Zealand. It forms dense, single-species stands in coastal areas. It has particularly spread from campground plantings in state parks along the central and southern coast. It can sprout easily after fire when top-killed, and its purple fruits are attractive to birds, which disperse them (Kitz 2000b). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
