    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of these trees includes Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Great Valley (262A), and Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands at Devereux Slough in Santa Barbara Co. (Sandoval 2004) in Santa
Barbara Co. and at Morro Strand State Beach (Walgren et al. 2005) in San Luis Obispo Co. contain few herbaceous plants.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands of <i>Schinus molle</i> from the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) in Ventura Co. include a shrub layer of <i>Artemisia californica, Baccharis pilularis, Encelia californica, Eriogonum fasciculatum, Lotus scoparius, Malosma laurina</i>, and <i>Salvia leucophylla</i>. Other stands along the Santa Clara River contain <i>Baccharis salicifolia, Encelia californica, Lepidospartum squamatum</i>, and <i>Salvia mellifera</i> (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007). Observations of <i>M. laetum</i> stands include stands at the San Dieguito Lagoon (CNPS unpublished data), in San Juan Capistrano, along the Santa Clara River with <i>Arundo donax</i> and <i>Baccharis pilularis</i>, and at McGrath State Beach (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). Stands from western Riverside Co. include <i>S. molle</i> (D. Bramlet, pers. comm. 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Both <i>Schinus </i>grow well in dry, nutrient soils and are tolerant of air pollution. <i>M. laetum </i>frequents disturbed coastal habitats. DiTomaso and Healey (2007) recommend cutting or burning mature trees to stimulate sprouting, and then removing sprouts and seedlings for three years. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
            <ul class="text">
                
                    <li>Myoporum laetum / Arundo donax [2]</li>
                
                    <li>Schinus molle [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Schinus molle / Lepidospartum squamatum [2]</li>
                
            </ul>
        
    </div>

    
